reviewText: We just signed up for HBO this year, and immediately became addicted to this hilarious show.  Now we want to see all of the episodes we have missed -- come on HBO, I Want My Curb Your Enthusiasm!

I am crushed that they do not even have the first seasons on DVD.  I just got HBO this year for the Sopranos, a very good show, but it isn't what I looked forward to the most!  CYE is absolutely genious.  It would be a crime if HBO didn't release a DVD compilation set of the 3 seasons.  I've only seen about 4 episodes and I'm totally hooked.  Hopefully HBO will get on it soon.  If you are reading this on the sight, make sure you put your email in at the top to let HBO know that you want it!

Larry David. Just looking at a picture of him can make me laugh. This show is not for everybody. But for those who watched Seinfeld, David is sort of a combination of George and Jerry. He seems to mean well and have a good heart but always lose in the end. Larry is the best. It was great seeing the show get a nomination for Best Comedy Series. Sunday nights just aren't quite Sunday nights without my "Curb" fix. Please bring out the DVD set soon HBO. Why haven't you put it out yet? I thought we were cool-de-la???
This is the funniest show i have ever seen, but i don't get to see all the episodes, because i just miss them because of buisiness conflicts. Release this series on DVD!

Theyve only showed a couple of episodes at 11:30pm, here in Australia, and axed the show, right when I got addicted to it. It grew on me slowly, the first time i watched i was trying to make sense of it all, then i realised you're not supposed to! Larry David is a comic genius! I cant wait till they bring out the dvd (hopefully all 3 seasons). I have no other way of watching this masterful comedy. I may move to the states just to watch it!

They are on weeknights. We never miss an episode.  We can't wait until the first and second season comes out on DVD!!!

All I can say is, believe the hype! Larry David along with sexy co-star Cheryl Hines make up some of the best 'husband and wife' comedic chemistry ever!

If you can stand Seinfeld with no language restrictions, this show is insanely great.  Larry David is a genius, and doesn't fear making himself look like a totally self-centered and horrid person.  The fact that his character is "Larry David, the Creator of Seinfeld" in the show wonderfully blurs the line between reality and fiction.
When you see this show, you will realize that the greatest part of the Seinfeld show was from the mind of Larry David.  This alone makes the show fascinating to watch.
There are wonderful recurring cameos by Jason Alexander, Julia Louis-Dreyfus, Richard Lewis, and a host of others.
There is a significant level of discomfort watching this show, and you might even find yourself yelling at the TV as Larry David digs himself into ever deeper holes through his habit of obfuscation and dissassembly.  The hilarious thing is that his intentions are generally good, but the result is disastrous.  It's wonderful that he never really learns why people end up despising him so much.  If he did, he wouldn't get into so much trouble and the show wouldn't be nearly as funny.
The humor is very REAL, despite coming from rather outlandish circumstances at times.  If you have any appreciation of existential humor, you MUST see this show.  It is a true treasure of modern comedy.

Larry David is a polarizing "comic" - you either love him or hate him.  He's just NOT funny - and I love comics!  The talented ones, anyway.  I sampled a few of these episodes to change my opinion of him, but no luck.  He's annoying, small-minded, vapid, self-absorbed, whiny, emotionally twisted . . . and on and on.  Comics are supposed to make you feel good!  Larry David is one big depressing buzz-kill!  I can't believe he even has a career - he must "know where the bodies are buried."

I am glad I finally got a chance to begin watching Curb Your Enthusiasm.  I am a huge long time Seinfeld fan and I was curious to see how  this show measured up with the 90's classic.  I certainly was not disappointed.  I would describe this show as Seinfeld with a bit of an edge, or Seinfeld with an R-rating.  Larry David has the same mundane observations of everyday life as a typical character in Seinfeld.  I thought it was also neat to have an occasional appearance of some of the primary stars of Seinfeld as well as some familiar faces of secondary characters on the show.  Curb Your Enthusiasm is an excellent show to turn on after a long day at work.  Laughs will come easily and often.

I was already a fan of Seinfeld and knew that Larry had been one of the creators (with Jerry). I had seen him perform as Steinbrunner and Castro and a few other parts on Seinfeld and liked all of those performances. Many of those did not involve seeing his face. So this show was the first time I got to see Larry in performance. I loved the show right from the start. I know some people had to grow into it but perhaps watching all of Seinfeld helped me accept it faster.

The show is Larry, supposedly in close to his real life persona. I am inclined to believe this is more true than not as his other roles are not far removed. He is totally obnoxious and that is half the fun. Equally as fun is that his obnoxious conduct usually gets him into hot water sooner or later. Very hot water. The supporting cast is great too. Jeff Garlin as his agent is wonderful and the comic who plays his wife Susie almost steals the entire show she is so funny.

Then there is Larry with anyone who is black. He is already pretty funny with anyone who is also Jewish but put him with someone who is black and he is in the stratosphere of comedy.

First off, I love Seinfeld and have seen every episode multiple times. I did not know a thing about curb your enthusiasm until 2005 when I bought season 4 from AAFES because it was a rental, cheap and the cover was funny. I don't usually like to start a series in the middle but I only had the one DVD set so I watched it and loved it. I bought every season I could with the intention of watching, but I had them in storage for a few days while I was moving and some A-hole broke into my unit and stole a lot of things, these DVD's being taken too.

Anyway, I just finished the whole series thanks to Amazon Prime. I binge watched it, and I usually don't do that. I started from Season 1 and just finished Season 8 yesterday, and I'm hoping LD comes out with a final season 9. Of course, I would ask for a season 10 after that, so it could go on forever. If you have Prime, give a few episodes a shot. It's not an acquired taste. I could watch any singular episode from any of the seasons and enjoy it.

The one thing I disliked was after season 6 they changed cameras or formats or something because it looks different. That's my only complaint. I liked it how it looked like it was an amateur TV show. 7&8 made it more professional looking. Not a bad thing, but if I have to nitpick something to dislike, it's that.

The whole series is packed with great performances. Other than LD, I absolutely love Richard Lewis in it, and wish he had a bigger role in the show. Other memorable roles are Bob Einstein as Marty Funkhouser, LD's "best friend", who I disliked at first but he really shined in the middle/later seasons. JB Smoove as Leon Black is really great as well. Of course Suzie and Jeff are awesome as LD's manager and wife. There's a lot of cameos too. I don't want to spoil it, just watch.

The worst part of the show is when the Blacks are basically pushed into the show. That's the only part of the show that seems real phony. It's still enjoyable, but the plot and everything else seem disheveled compared to previous seasons.

There's the mini Seinfeld reunion. Eh. Could have gone without it, but it's great seeing the gang back together.

Overall I love this series. Many many many Seinfeld show references if you know them pretty well.

All the things they could never have gotten away with on NBC, but here on HBO they had free reign... and the results are hilarious... George Costanza may have been based on Larry David, but here we see the version of Larry David's "George Costanza" after having spent half a lifetime with Jerry Seinfeld... Do yourself a favor and watch this series from beginning to end... This is perfect show for the modern day art of "binge-watching"... Enjoy!

Sure, I'm late to the Larry Lovefest.  But that doesn't mean my love is any less powerful or pure.  There is something sweetly disturbing going on in the life of LD.  Innocence meets ignorance and then gives birth to the most brilliant comedic scenes.  Sure, sometimes you cringe. But its not like "Hello, Ladies" kinda cringing where you violently grasp the nearest pillow to bury your face, while groaning in empathetic embarrassment for the lead character.  Its full frontal ridiculousness.  Like seeing a naked 102 year old man in pink stilettos.  Flexing his muscles in the mirror.  It is just that funny!  Get on board the Larry Loveboat and don't miss this masterpiece of comedy.

When you watch Curb, you understand where the quarky funny humor comes from... Larry David. Jerry Seinfeld is a mediocre comedian who has been thrust into comedy royalty from the sitcom that bears his name. But like any mediocre comedian, his snobbery is starting to show through (Comedians in Cars/Amy Schumer ep).

Larry David embraces his dislike for humanity by using Curb Your Enthusiasm as a vice for saying what we are all thinking at times, while playing out the scenario of potential results we would all experience for doing so with a comedic twist that keeps you coming back for more. And even though he has had two comedy hits now vs Jerry's one hit, he still manages to not be a d*** like Jerry has become.

This is a very funny show if you enjoy witty, albeit sarcastic, humor. Larry David plays a fictionalized, morallly questionable version of himself where he constantly  adresses the social norms of day to day life as a somewhat retired television writer in Los Angeles.

Cheryl Hines expertly plays the role of his wife who is often embarassed by Her husbands antics and rants and Jeff Garlin was casted as his always-funny manager.

The HBO show witnesses a plethora of cameos made by other famous hollywood celebrities living in or near Los Angeles as as well. The fact that the show aired on HBO makes it unsuitable for a young audience, anyone under 18, due to the writing's somewhat crude and raunchy nature.

The only part of the show that seems to grow old is the fact that many of the scenes contain people consistently talking over others, while exemplifying Larry's crazy antics, becomes somewhat annoying.

Overall, this is a very funny show that is definitely worth a watch if you are into somewhat dark and critical humor as is seemingly always carried out by Larry David.

"Curb Your Enthusiasm," reading the description of it, I thought it would be humorous and fun to watch.  However, what I discovered is a lot of sexual content and innuendo that I just don't care for and don't want to listen to.  I am a firm believer that innuendo is fine, but then this show crosses the line into just blatant sexual humor that, quite honestly, I don't think is that funny.  Maybe my age is showing but I just think that some things can be left to the imagination and don't need to be so overly-sexualized in content.  There is so much humor in life that doesn't revolve around sex, sexual parts, and sexual acts.  I wish comedians would step back and realize that sometimes less is more...and not all of us are so singlemindedly sex-crazed.  I didn't even make it through the entire first episode and am quite sure that I won't watch this show again.

The other day I asked a guy I know at a food stand in a vegan fair, if I could have a half serve because I had eaten so much that day that I felt stuffed, but I really wanted to try his dish. He was more than happy to give it me, and in fact, he didn't even charge me. A little later, a friend of mine who was working at the fair, asked if I would get her some cake from another stall, but they didn't have spoons, so I went back to the guy who gave me the small serve and asked if I could have one of his disposable spoons and he gave me a funny look and kind of begrudgingly said yes. I thought it was a bit strange until minute later, I realized that he was probably wondering, "why would he want a spoon for some food if he is already full and only wanted a small serve of my food". So the next day, I had to go back and order a full serve, just to make sure he was happy with me, because it was too hard to explain something that was probably not real anyway, maybe I misread his disgruntled look.

This is the type of every day confusion that Larry David writes about, but he gives it a test and then segues into the B, A or even C story so seamlessly, that you don't see it coming.  It is hilarious.

Love this show and love Larry David.  Show is sometimes absurd and funny and sometimes hits on real everyday situations we all encounter and are annoyed by, where Mr. David can find humor. Our series (with a few exceptions here and there) are trite, and poorly acted.  Seems the US is more concerned with  putting beautiful people bulging out of their clothes on the screen as opposed to fine actors. Neurotic, witty, sometimes dark, but always funny, Larry David plays himself in this pseudo autobiographical sitcom loaded with popculture references and irreverant commentary on modern life for a somewhat not so modern man. The humor presented mostly comes from the outrageous situations LD and his friends/family find themselves in, usually involving a social faux pas or two. There are many celebrity cameos as well, and I particularly enjoyed seeing Jason Alexander getting some work. There are layers and layers of inside jokes and subtle jabs at everyone and everything, from Kathy Griffin to charity work. I highly recommend this series for anyone who is a fan of laughing/chuckling/guffawing or giggling. Snickerers may or may not enjoy.

It has a Seinfeld feel to it (Larry is the co-creator of that show), and at times, Larry delivers his lines in a similar way, so if you like that show, you will probably like this one, too. Laugh-out-loud comedy about the mostly unintentionally inappropriate behavior of Larry David, a fictionalized version of  the real-life co-creator of Seinfeld. Curb your Enthusiasm is similar to Seinfeld with it's absurd premises (eg cut-off time for evening calls, the perils of an extra fold of material in crotch region, star-struck neighbors with a sense of entitlement, an obituary with an unfortunate typo) but Curb is smarter and funnier. The show is partially improvised featuring hilarious supporting characters: Larry's put-upon and smarter wife, his well intentioned but mischievous manager and his foul mouthed wife, and Larry's neurotic best friend (Richard Lewis). There are guest stars playing a version of themselves or entirely different characters.  Curb is always good for a laugh!

Based on the numerous other 5 star reviews, I realize I'm in the minority of not liking this show.  It's my personal opinion, but I think Larry David is annoying as an actor.  His voice is extremely irritating to me, mostly because he voiced the George Steinbrenner character on Seinfeld and that's all I hear when he talks.  That's my problem, but Larry David uses so much of the same dialogue from the Steinbrenner character from Seinfeld that's it's lazy and irritating to the viewer.  So much of this show was already done on Seinfeld, Larry David just reuses the Seinfeld dialogue and storylines, plus he seems to be imitating Jerry Seinfeld when he acts.

This show wants viewers to believe this is Larry David's real life with a little TV magic to blur the line between fiction and real life.  Viewers are expected to believe Larry David is a normal guy that does normal everyday things and just happens to have funny and awkward things happen to him.  The scenarios are so obviously invented and written, it's typical TV because they have to fill 30 minutes.  The episodes are predictable, situations are artificially complicated to fill 30 minutes.  The issues that happen in the episodes aren't believable, Larry David has over $100 million dollars and wouldn't be in these situations.

So glad Amazon has added Curb your enthusiasm to Prime, a really funny situation comedy. Love all the characters and actors portraying them. If you're offended by filthy language or controversial issues, this is not for you. If you can get over yourself and just enjoy the comedy,  subject material and pure satire, this is your place to look at yourself.

Larry David's mind is a wonder to behold.  His thoughts manifest in Curb Your Enthusiasm keep me laughing, groaning, exclaiming, believing and disbelieving. I think the entire series is genius. Besides the ironic, wry look at the life of a rich born loser, the episodes also provide a look into the lives of wealthy Los Angeles area people. Turns out they're just like the rest of us except they have money to smooth over their stupid behavior. Curb Your Enthusiasm is not a series I can binge on. After a while, I get tired of Larry being obtuse, literal, and annoying. I watch a few episodes and then take a break. I've seen almost all of Curb. When I want to binge on it, I chose episodes I enjoy because he goes light on being always morose.  Don't  think it's like Seinfeld with swearing but there ae some inside jokes you'll enjoy if you are a Seinfeld fan.

The ability to take simple things of life and turn them into a story that is not only very humorous and whimsical is perhaps the most difficult of sitcom writing. The wit here is an undercurrent that stretches the imagination in unusual ways and the just when you believe there is no more to be heard, an additional piece comes on board. May be one of the best shows ever written.  It's Seinfeld (another top 10 show of ALL TIME) on a whole new level of comedy.  It shows the true genius of Larry David and how funny a sitcom can be without network or studio input.  This show is well acted and written (well great story lines).  Larry doesn't write most of the show, he outlines and "improv's" most of it.  He does a story outline and the actors improvisational a good portion of the scene.  Isn't Larry a GENIUS!!!  Get ready to laugh and have the best time of your life.  I watch this show when I can and it still makes me laugh.  I have seen some episodes up to 20 times.  My favorite is the water bottle with the little girl in the bathroom (THE DOLL) episode and the Dodger Game with the "lady of the evening" so he can use the carpool lane (THE CAR POOL LANE).  His episode titles are so easy to remember.  Hey that episode kept a man out of prison for REAL (google it).  I can't say enough on how good this show is to watch.  Do yourself a favor and watch it if you never have seen an episode.  Each year get's better and better.  How many times can you say that about a TV show.  Well, Seinfeld of course.  HBO and I hope both hope that Larry does another season soon.  He has an open contract with HBO, so he can if he wants.  PLEASE LARRY, more "Curb" soon!!!  You are my ######.  I can't say it but all you Curb fans know what I mean.  Great cameo's too.  From Alanis Morissette to the cast of Seinfeld.  I love this show
